# AGENTS.md — {{project}} (fractal swarm)

Operator-style agent rules for solo AI **and** multi-agent L0/L1 waves.
Distilled from cabal-devmelopner house style — product-specific paths removed.

## Tero-first (corpus memory)

When a Tero / Layer-1 index is available, **query it before large greps**.

Prefer:

1. `text_search` / `query_by_id` / `query_by_kind` via the `tero` MCP server
2. Open the **cited file:line** — hits are pointers, not ground truth
3. On refusal (`kind: refusal` / no citable match), rephrase or fall back to repo search

### Cold start (no `tero__*` tools)

Sessions only pick up MCP servers registered before launch. Register Tero, then
`/mcps` → `r` or start a new session. See sibling `tero-mcp` and your index path.

Token default for local work: `local-dev` (or whatever matches `TERO_TOKENS`).

## Subagents and multi-repo excavation

Orchestrator **and** leaf subagents should excavate with Tero first, then verify
against local trees.

**Orchestrator checklist when spawning investigation agents:**

1. Confirm `tero__identify` (or `search_tool` → `tero__*`) works
2. Paste an explicit **Tero excavation block** into every subagent prompt
3. Prefer leaf prompts that name **ids to chase** when known
4. After leaves return, `cross_ref` / `query_by_id` on new ids the leaves surfaced

**Paste into each investigation subagent prompt:**

```text
## Tero excavation (do this before deep filesystem greps)

You have access to the `tero` MCP server (tools `tero__*`). Use it to excavate
project memory related to your target. Token: "local-dev" (or env TERO_TOKEN).

1. search_tool query="tero" once if needed to refresh schemas.
2. tero__identify { "token": "local-dev" } — confirm index is live.
3. tero__text_search { "value": "<target + keywords>", "token": "local-dev" }
4. For each strong hit with an id: tero__query_by_id
5. tero__cross_ref { "start": "<id>", "depth": "2", "token": "local-dev" } when mapping programs
6. Open cited file:line paths — summaries are not ground truth.
7. Only then dig the local checkout (branches, README, src, tests).

If tero__* tools are missing: note "Tero unavailable" and fall back to repo search;
tell the orchestrator to fix MCP registration for the next wave.
```

## Model policy (L0 / L1)

See **docs/MODEL_POLICY.md** (or the snippet installed with this profile):

| Role | Model class | Use for |
|------|-------------|---------|
| **L0** | Frontier (hard architecture, naming, design forks) | Rare; only when L0 is named |
| **L1** | Composer / fast implementer (default) | Code, docs, extraction, PRs |

- **No automatic Copilot code review** (fleet-wide)
- Copilot instructions file is opt-in only; reviews stay off

## Local checks

```bash
./scripts/check.sh
./scripts/check.sh --fix    # apply formatters when supported
./scripts/check.sh --quick   # faster path when supported
```

Run gates before claiming complete. Prefer small, reviewable diffs.

## Branch / worktree guards

- Never commit directly to `main` (or protected `dev` without a PR)
- Create feature / chore / fix branches from the correct base
- Prefer one worktree per concurrent wave when using multi-agent orchestration
- Append-only for living docs (`AGENTS.md`, kickoffs, ROADMAP status sections)

## PR tiers — Refs vs Closes

| Target | Keywords | Effect |
|--------|----------|--------|
| Feature → `dev` | **`Refs #n`**, `Related to #n` | Issues stay open |
| Delivery → `main` | **`Closes #n`**, **`Fixes #n`** | Issues close on merge |
| Epic | `Closes #<epic>` only on full main delivery | Partial work uses Refs |

Fleet workflows:

- `close-issues-on-main.yml` — closes linked issues when PR lands on **main**
- `reopen-issues-closed-off-main.yml` — reopens if `Closes` was used off-main

Do **not** request automatic Copilot review on PRs.

